# excercise 2 Perform exploratory data analysis (EDA) on with datasets like email data set. Export all your emails as a dataset, import
# them inside a pandas data frame, visualize them and getdifferent insights from the data.

import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import seaborn as sns
from datetime import datetime
import random

sample_emails = [
    {'Date': '2025-07-10 08:30', 'From': 'alice@gmail.com', 'To': 'you@gmail.com',
     'Subject': 'Meeting Update', 'Body': 'Let’s reschedule our meeting to tomorrow.'},
    {'Date': '2025-07-11 10:45', 'From': 'bob@yahoo.com', 'To': 'you@gmail.com',
     'Subject': 'Project Submission', 'Body': 'Project has been submitted successfully.'},
    {'Date': '2025-07-11 14:15', 'From': 'charlie@ritchennai.edu.in', 'To': 'you@gmail.com',
     'Subject': 'Internship Info', 'Body': 'Please find the attached internship details.'},
    {'Date': '2025-07-12 09:20', 'From': 'dave@amazon.com', 'To': 'you@gmail.com',
     'Subject': 'Order Confirmation', 'Body': 'Your order has been shipped.'},
    {'Date': '2025-07-13 17:00', 'From': 'alice@gmail.com', 'To': 'you@gmail.com',
     'Subject': 'Follow Up', 'Body': 'Just following up on our last conversation.'},
    {'Date': '2025-07-13 18:20', 'From': 'newsletter@udemy.com', 'To': 'you@gmail.com',
     'Subject': 'Course Discount', 'Body': 'Get 90% off on all Python courses today only!'},
]
df = pd.DataFrame(sample_emails)
df['Date'] = pd.to_datetime(df['Date'])
df['Body_Length'] = df['Body'].str.len()
df['Domain'] = df['From'].str.extract(r'@([\w\.-]+)')
df['Date_Only'] = df['Date'].dt.date

print("Basic Info:")
print(df.info())
print("\nSample Data:")
print(df.head())

plt.figure(figsize=(10,5))
df['Date_Only'].value_counts().sort_index().plot(kind='line', marker='o')
plt.title("Emails Over Time")
plt.xlabel("Date")
plt.ylabel("Number of Emails")
plt.grid()
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

plt.figure(figsize=(8,5))
df['From'].value_counts().plot(kind='bar', color='skyblue')
plt.title("Top Senders")
plt.ylabel("Number of Emails")
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

plt.figure(figsize=(8,5))
df['Domain'].value_counts().plot(kind='pie', autopct='%1.1f%%', startangle=140)
plt.title("Email Domains")
plt.ylabel("")
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

plt.figure(figsize=(8,5))
sns.histplot(df['Body_Length'], bins=10, kde=True, color='coral')
plt.title("Body Length Distribution")
plt.xlabel("Characters in Body")
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

# excercise 3 Working with Nupy arrays, Pandas data frames, Basic plots using Matplotlib.Numpy arrays using matplotlib

import numpy as np
from matplotlib import pyplot as plt
import pandas as pd
x = np.arange(1,11)
y = 2 * x + 5
plt.title("Matplotlib demo")
plt.xlabel("x axis caption")
plt.ylabel("y axis caption")
plt.plot(x,y)
plt.show()

df = pd.DataFrame({'Name': ['John', 'Sammy', 'Joe'],'Age': [45, 38, 90]})
df.plot(x="Name", y="Age", kind="bar")
plt.show()

x = [1,1.5,2,2.5,3,3.5,3.6]
y = [7.5,8,8.5,9,9.5,10,10.5]
x1=[8,8.5,9,9.5,10,10.5,11]
y1=[3,3.5,3.7,4,4.5,5,5.2]

plt.ylabel('income*1000')
plt.title('Scatter Plot')
plt.legend()
plt.show()

# excercise 5 Perform Time Series Analysis and apply the various visualization techniques.

import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import seaborn as sns

sns.set(style="whitegrid")
data = {
    'Time': pd.date_range(start='2025-01-01', periods=10, freq='D'),
    'Value': [10, 12, 14, 13, 15, 16, 18, 17, 19, 20]
}
df = pd.DataFrame(data)
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
plt.plot(df['Time'], df['Value'], color='blue', linewidth=2, marker='o', markersize=8, markerfacecolor='white', markeredgecolor='black')
plt.title("Time Series Plot", fontsize=16, fontweight='bold')
plt.xlabel("Time", fontsize=12)
plt.ylabel("Value", fontsize=12)
plt.xticks(rotation=45)
plt.grid(True, linestyle='--', alpha=0.5)
plt.tight_layout()

max_idx = df['Value'].idxmax()
plt.annotate('Highest Point',
             xy=(df['Time'][max_idx], df['Value'][max_idx]),
             xytext=(df['Time'][max_idx], df['Value'][max_idx] + 1.5),
             arrowprops=dict(facecolor='black', arrowstyle='->'),
             fontsize=10)

plt.show()

#exercise 6
import folium
import pandas as pd
data = pd.read_csv("your_data.csv")

center_lat = data['lat'].mean()
center_lon = data['lon'].mean()
m = folium.Map(location=[center_lat, center_lon], zoom_start=5)

location_data = data.groupby(['lat', 'lon']).size().reset_index(name='count')
for i in range(len(location_data)):
    lat = location_data.iloc[i]['lat']
    lon = location_data.iloc[i]['lon']
    count = location_data.iloc[i]['count']
    
    popup_text = folium.Popup(f' Count: {count}', parse_html=True)
    
    folium.Marker(
        location=[lat, lon],
        popup=popup_text,
        icon=folium.Icon(color='red', icon='info-sign')
    ).add_to(m)

folium.LayerControl().add_to(m)
m

#exercise 7 Build cartographic visualization for multiple datasets involving various countries of the worldstates and districts in India etc
import folium
import pandas as pd
from IPython.display import display
world_geo = 'https://raw.githubusercontent.com/python-visualization/folium/master/examples/data/world-countries.json'
data = {
    'Country': ['United States', 'China', 'India', 'Brazil', 'Germany'],
    'GDP_per_capita': [65000, 10000, 2500, 9000, 50000]
}
df = pd.DataFrame(data)

m = folium.Map(location=[20, 0], zoom_start=2)

folium.Choropleth(
    geo_data=world_geo,
    data=df,
    columns=['Country', 'GDP_per_capita'],
    key_on='feature.properties.name',
    fill_color='YlGnBu',
    fill_opacity=0.7,
    line_opacity=0.2,
    legend_name='GDP per Capita (USD)'
).add_to(m)

m.save('simple_choropleth.html')
m

# excercise 8 Perform EDA on Wine Quality Data Set
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import seaborn as sns

# Load the dataset properly (skip index column)
data = pd.read_csv('winequality-red.csv', index_col=0)

# Basic Info
print(data.head())
print(data.info())
print(data.describe())
print("Missing values:\n", data.isnull().sum())

# Quality Distribution
sns.countplot(x='quality', data=data)
plt.title('Wine Quality Distribution')
plt.show()

# Histograms
data.hist(bins=50, figsize=(15, 10))
plt.suptitle('Feature Distributions')
plt.show()

# Correlation Heatmap
plt.figure(figsize=(12, 8))
sns.heatmap(data.corr(), annot=True, cmap='coolwarm')
plt.title('Feature Correlation Heatmap')
plt.show()
